he state from one that was focused on juridical exclusion to one of inclusion. The new relationship then enabled affected groups to demand rights and citizenship from the Indian state that had been previously unimaginable. By illuminating such tactics as mobilizing against a colonial era anti-sodomy law, petitioning the courts for the recognition of gender identity, and stalling attempts to criminalize sexual labor, this book uniquely brings together the struggles of sex workers, transgender people, and gay groups previously studied separately. A closely observed look at the machinations behind recent victories for sexual minorities, this book is essential reading across several fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAIDS (Disease)xPatientsxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspectszIndia. 0aAIDS activistszIndia. 0aSex workersxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspectszIndia. 0aSexual minoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspectszIndia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aCBOs.  aHIV.  aImmoral Traffic Prevention Act (ITPA).  aKoushal.  aLGBTQ.  aMSM.  aNALSA.  aNGOs.  aSupreme Court of India.  aanti-sodomy law (Section 377).  aanti-trafficking.  abare life.  abiopower.  aconstitutional morality.  aenchantment of the state.  agovernmentality.  ahigh-risk groups.  ahijra.  ahijras.  ainterconnectedness of rights.  ajuridical power.  akothi.  apeer educators.  apolitical subjectivities.  asex work.  asex workers.  asexual acts.  asexual identities.  asexual minorities.  asocial movements.  asolidarity building.  astate violence.  atargeted interventions.  atransgender persons.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEB